{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b92dcbc8-a2c9-4d33-be7d-08f7294ede7b","content":"The working directory is empty, so I'll answer from knowledge.\n\nThe switch is straightforward — just **remove** (or set to `false`) the `<UseVSTest>` property. With **MSTest.Sdk 3.8.0**, Microsoft.Testing.Platform is the **default** runner, so no additional packages are needed.\n\n### In your `.csproj` / `Directory.Build.props`:\n\n```xml\n<!-- Before -->\n<Project Sdk=\"MSTest.Sdk/3.8.0\">\n  <PropertyGroup>\n    <UseVSTest>true</UseVSTest>   <!-- ← delete this line -->\n  </PropertyGroup>\n</Project>\n```\n\n```xml\n<!-- After -->\n<Project Sdk=\"MSTest.Sdk/3.8.0\">\n  <PropertyGroup>\n    <!-- no UseVSTest property needed -->\n  </PropertyGroup>\n</Project>\n```\n\n### Key things to be aware of:\n\n1. **CLI changes** — `dotnet test` still works, but the test executable is now directly runnable (`dotnet run --project Tests.csproj -- --list-tests`).\n2. **`.runsettings`** — Still supported, but some VSTest-specific adapter settings may not carry over. Review any custom runsettings.\n3. **CI/CD** — If your pipeline relies on `--logger trx`, use `--report-trx` instead (or add `<OutputType>Exe</OutputType>` if not already implied by the SDK).\n4. **Extensions** — VSTest adapters (e.g., coverlet with `--collect`) are replaced by Microsoft.Testing.Platform extensions. For code coverage, use `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.CodeCoverage` or pass `--coverage`.\n\nThat's it — removing `<UseVSTest>true</UseVSTest>` is the only required change.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"aa7bb974-5977-4d17-9914-1d51d32c81a8","outputTokens":438,"requestId":"E3EA:3D936D:1619E63:18B9999:6A05204C"},"id":"0e0e01b4-2355-4ebf-87a9-8bd57bd9dd00","timestamp":"2026-05-14T01:07:34.798Z","parentId":"70e96c01-8b03-433e-a230-d8df2387e1f3"}
